<HEADLINE>
<P>
CARROLL P. (SPUD) CORLISS; LONGTIME REPORTER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Carroll P. (Spud) Corliss, 86, a journalist who spent 40 years on the police 
and government beats in Los Angeles before retiring in 1968. He began in 1928 
as a reporter on the old Los Angeles Express, worked for papers in Pasadena and 
as night news editor of radio station KECA before coming to The Times in 1948. 
He was one of the first newsmen on the scene of the Watts riots in 1965 and 
covered countless major disasters and news events, including the assassination 
of Robert F. Kennedy. In Ashland, Ore., on Saturday of cancer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
