</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Senate today approved an $8.5-billion military construction bill that 
slashes President Bush's request for bases overseas but adds millions of 
dollars for domestic projects. 
</P>
<P>
By voice vote, the Senate adopted the legislation and sent it to Bush for his 
signature. 
</P>
<P>
The bill cuts military construction spending in fiscal 1990 by $461 million 
from what was spent during the fiscal year that ended Sept. 30 and is $65 
million below what Bush wanted to spend this year. 
</P>
<P>
"I think we've seen the peak of military construction spending for many years 
to come," said Sen. Jim Sasser (D-Tenn.), chairman of the Senate Appropriations 
subcommittee on military construction. "Next year may be even smaller than the 
bill here today." 
